I understood that and it did cause me to pause.  But in the end I'm not sure what he said is what he really meant... or rather I think he was fighting two battles.<br>
<br>
a) giving a free guide, fine. free, yay. friendly neighbor and all that.<br>
b) emphasizing (multiple times) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>free</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> while ranting against buying/selling of accounts... implying that they could save their money and do the work themselves (nevermind that raising ~$600 is work).<br>
<br>
In the end it was the years of advertising doublespeak that made me post.<br>
<br>
Get rich quick! Take our $500 weekend course!<br>
<br>
Applying for gov't jobs is free!  Buy this guide to show you how!<br>
<br>
Welfare tips pamphlet $19.95.<br>
<br>
Not that those are shining examples... I just saw a similarity between his free guide illustrating how to spend all sorts of money (and time) to accomplish something that essentially can be done in a fraction of the time with roughly the same amount of money (if you have it as a lump sum).<br>
